prj:ScienceGoal.prj:name: Orion Starless Cores
prj:ScienceGoal.prj:note: Observe Orion starless cores in 3mm continuum and 12CO1-0.

prj:TechnicalJustification.prj:justificationText:
Three out of the four basebands will be used to observe the continuum, and are thus set to the lowest spectral resolution and largest bandwidth (1.875 GHz bandwidth, 31 MHz spectral resolution). The fourth baseband will be used to observe CO (1-0). Outflows can extend up to 50-75 km/s from rest, so we select the correlator mode that provides ~150 km/s of total bandwidth (75 km/s from rest in each direction). Even the lowest velocity outflows extend at least ~3 km/s from rest, so we use spectral averaging to reduce the resolution to ~0.3 km/s and guarantee at least ten spectral resolution elements per outflow - further averaging would begin to compromise our ability to resolve the velocity structure and mass and energy spectrum of the outflow. Based on the above sensitivity discussion, we will further smooth to 0.5 km/s for the weakest outflows, as required.
The representative spectral window is one of the continuum basebands with a very low spectral resolution, thus the note in the OT that the line may not be resolved is not applicable.
This setup produces a very low data rate (1.37 MB/s for the 12-m, 0.59 MB/s for the ACA 7-m).

The cores in our survey have a typical size of 20", with a maximum size of 30" for the largest cores, but the sub-structure will be (by definition) much smaller than this. We request an angular resolution of 1.3", chosen to match the linear resolution of the cycle 1 Cham I and cycle 2 Ophiuchus data (~450 AU). Both our simulations and results from the Ophiuchus observations confirm this resolution is required in order to resolve individual fragments within cores.
The largest angular scale of 30" is set so that we can fully recover emission from all of the cores in our sample. This results in the use of the ACA 7-m antennas. As we show in Figure 2 of the proposal, our simulations show that recovery up to these scales significantly improves our ability to recover the full structure of the cores and allows us to identify fragmentation to earlier evolutionary times (and thus lower core densities).

Our sensitivity requirement is based on the continuum, justifying that the bandwidth used for sensitivity is much wider than the line of interest (the line of interest is a secondary goal). As explained in the proposal text, we base our sensitivity requirement on the ability to detect substructure in starless cores. Taking the average core mass and radius we first calculate the mean surface density of each core. We then set our sensitivity such that we can detect, with at least 5sigma significance, compact fragments with surface densities at least 10x higher than this mean value. Assuming standard dust opacities and temperatures as given in the proposal text (kappa = 0.003 cm^2/g at 115 GHz, T = 20 K), this results in a required 1sigma sensitivity of 0.07 mJy/beam. The peak flux densities of 5 mJy are estimated from the MHD simulations shown in Figures 1 and 2 of the proposal.
While the primary focus of this proposal is the continuum, we will use one of the four basebands to observe CO (1-0) in order to identify outflows from hidden protostars. With the integration time set by the continuum sensitivity as described above, we will obtain a 1sigma line sensitivity of 1.1 K in 0.5 km/s channels (1.3" beam). Outflows are typically >5K over at least 2-3 km/s from rest, guaranteeing >~5sigma detections from any protostars lurking in our 'starless' core sample.

prp:ObsProposal.prp:abstract: Recent interferometric surveys of starless cores have found that 1) 5-20% of these objects actually harbor low-luminosity star-forming objects, and 2) none of the truly starless cores have any detectable substructure or evidence for fragmentation. These surveys, however, were intentionally biased and suffer from small sample sizes. To begin to address this problem, we have conducted ALMA surveys of starless cores in Chamaeleon I (cycle 1) and Ophiuchus (cycle 2). We have detected evidence for both starless core fragmentation and hidden protostars in the Ophiuchus sample, and have used nondetections in the Chamaeleon I sample to constrain the evolutionary stage of the starless core population in this cloud. Here we re-propose to survey starless cores in Orion B North (filler time in Cycle 2, no data yet obtained) in order to complete our survey of starless cores across diverse environments. We will determine definitive classifications (starless or protostellar), discriminate between models of star formation that predict different paths for the origin of binary protostellar systems, and test the extent to which the environment influences the path(s) of star formation.
